[3] England
Date: Mon 21 May 2018 16:49 BST
Source: Mail Online [edited]
http://www.dailymail.co.uk/health/article-5753851/Measles-outbreak-warning-Fifteen-confirmed-sufferers-secondary-school-West-Sussex.html


Measles outbreak warning: 15 sufferers are confirmed at a secondary school in West Sussex as cases rocket across England due to an epidemic in Europe
----------------------------------------------------------------
Summary:
- Between 1 Jan and 9 May 2018, 440 cases have been confirmed in England.
- Outbreaks are occurring in Italy, Germany, Greece, France, and Romania.
-To prevent an outbreak, 95 percent of the population should be immunised.
- Only 91.9 percent of children were vaccinated against measles between 2015 and 2016.
- Andrew Wakefield's discredited MMR-autism theory may be to blame.

According to Public Health England (PHE), 15 students from Chichester High School in West Sussex have been diagnosed with measles.

This comes after figures released earlier this month [May 2018] revealed that between 1 Jan and 9 May 2018, 440 cases of measles were confirmed in England, with London being the worst hit.

PHE claims travel between European countries experiencing measles epidemics is behind England's outbreak, as well as people failing to take up the recommended measles, mumps and rubella (MMR) vaccines.

Dr Mary Ramsay, head of immunisation at PHE, previously said: "The majority of cases we are seeing are in teenagers and young adults who missed out on their MMR vaccine when they were children."

Romania, Italy, Germany, Greece, and France are all experiencing unprecedented cases of the highly infectious, life-threatening condition.

To prevent a measles outbreak, it is recommended that 95 per cent of the population is immunised against the infection.

Only 91.9 per cent of children were vaccinated against measles between 2015 and 2016 compared to 94.2 per cent in 2014-to-2015 and 94.3 per cent in 2013-to-2014, according to NHS immunisation statistics.

The 'elimination' of measles has been achieved in the UK, global health leaders said in September [2017]. The elimination of measles or rubella can be verified once a country has sustained 'interruption of endemic transmission' for at least 36 months, according to the World Health Organization (WHO).

The European Regional Verification Commission said the UK achieved elimination status for measles as of 2016. Dr Mary Ramsay, head of immunisation at Public Health England, said: "We are delighted that the WHO has confirmed that the UK achieved measles elimination in 2016 and that rubella elimination continues to be sustained.

"In addition, national vaccine coverage of the 1st MMR dose in 5-year-olds has hit the WHO's 95 per cent target. ..."

What were the measles, mumps, and rubella vaccination rates in 2-year-olds across England in 2015-to-2016? [see source URL above for figure]

"While the cases in Chichester are among children, it is important to remember that measles is not just a childhood illness, as proven by the number of recent cases among adults in other parts of Sussex and Surrey. ..."

Since January 2018, Surrey and Sussex have had 70 confirmed measles cases, compared with 20 in the same time period last year [2017].

Where in England are outbreaks occurring?
London has had the most measles cases, with a confirmed 164 incidences so far this year [2018]. This is followed by the South East where 86 people have suffered since 1 Jan 2018. The West Midlands has had 78 incidences and the South West 42. West Yorkshire is also experiencing a local outbreak with 37 confirmed cases in just over 5 months.

Dr Ramsay said: "The measles outbreaks we are currently seeing in England are linked to ongoing large outbreaks in Europe.

"The majority of cases we are seeing are in teenagers and young adults who missed out on their MMR vaccine when they were children. ..."

Epidemics in Europe
-------------------
Earlier this year [2018], the WHO warned measles was spreading across Europe in regions where vaccination rates are low, such as Poland, Switzerland, and Ukraine.

Data published in November last year [2017] by the European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control [ECDC] in the Communicable Disease Threat Report show that from January 2016-November 2017, more than 19 000 measles cases were reported in the EU, including 46 deaths.

The highest number of cases in 2017 were reported in Romania, where 7759 people suffered, followed by Italy with 4775 cases, and Germany with 898 sufferers. Greece also experienced a measles outbreak, with at least 368 cases, and 1 death, since May 2017.

Dr Ramsay said: "Due to ongoing measles outbreaks within Europe, we will continue to see imported measles cases in the UK in unimmunised individuals. ..."

Fears over discredited claims the jab causes autism may be to blame for outbreaks. Are autistic children missing out on vaccinations? Autistic children are missing out on life-saving vaccinations, research suggested in March 2018.

Only 81.6 per cent of those on the autism spectrum have received all the recommended vaccinations for children aged between 4 and 6 years old, a study found.

For those without the developmental disability, 94.1 per cent have had the necessary jabs, including diphtheria, polio, and measles, mumps, and rubella (MMR), the research adds.

Lead author Dr Ousseny Zerbo, from Kaiser Permanente, California, said: "These findings suggest that children with autism and their younger siblings may be at greater risk of vaccine-preventable diseases.

"Vaccine hesitancy or refusal may play a role in children not getting properly vaccinated."

Results further suggest just 89.1 per cent of children with autism have been vaccinated against diphtheria, tetanus and whooping cough, compared to 96.6 per cent of youngsters without the disorder.

Only 84 per cent of autistic children are protected against MMR versus 95.9 per cent who do not suffer such developmental and behavioural challenges.

The younger siblings of autism sufferers are also missing out, with 6.8 per cent receiving fewer vital jabs than their peers. ...

